1
00:00:28,132 --> 00:00:32,262
<i>...what has turned into
a classic Formula 1 season.</i>

2
00:00:33,892 --> 00:00:35,860
<i>With the weather conditions
so uncertain,</i>

3
00:00:35,972 --> 00:00:37,178
<i>the drivers prepare for...</i>

4
00:00:39,812 --> 00:00:41,814
<i>...the track is still dangerously wet,</i>

5
00:00:41,852 --> 00:00:43,263
<i>but following a drivers' meeting,</i>

6
00:00:43,332 --> 00:00:46,415
<i>- a decision has finally been taken.
- Three minutes to go.</i>

7
00:00:47,092 --> 00:00:49,174
<i>Everybody off the grid now.</i>

8
00:01:03,172 --> 00:01:07,257
<i>Twenty-five drivers
start every season in Formula 1,</i>

9
00:01:07,332 --> 00:01:10,415
<i>and each year two of us die.</i>

10
00:01:11,172 --> 00:01:13,539
<i>What kind of person
does a job like this?</i>

11
00:01:14,692 --> 00:01:16,694
<i>Not normal men, for sure.</i>

12
00:01:16,772 --> 00:01:21,016
<i>Rebels, lunatics, dreamers.</i>

13
00:01:21,692 --> 00:01:24,093
<i>People who are desperate to make a mark</i>

14
00:01:24,212 --> 00:01:26,453
<i>and are prepared to die trying.</i>

15
00:01:28,532 --> 00:01:29,897
<i>My name is Niki Lauda,</i>

16
00:01:30,252 --> 00:01:33,381
<i>and racing people
know me for two things.</i>

17
00:01:33,452 --> 00:01:37,218
<i>The first is my rivalry with him.</i>

18
00:01:41,372 --> 00:01:44,296
<i>Photographers,
please clear the grid.</i>

19
00:01:44,812 --> 00:01:46,780
What about Hunt? Has he changed?

20
00:01:47,052 --> 00:01:48,497
No, he's going on wets.

21
00:01:48,572 --> 00:01:51,735
<i>I don't know
why it became such a big thing.</i>

22
00:01:51,772 --> 00:01:55,140
<i>We were just drivers
busting each other's balls.</i>

23
00:01:56,132 --> 00:01:58,578
<i>To me this is perfectly normal,</i>

24
00:01:58,652 --> 00:02:00,814
<i>but other people saw it differently,</i>

25
00:02:00,892 --> 00:02:03,816
<i>that whatever it was between us
went deeper.</i>

26
00:02:20,092 --> 00:02:22,094
<i>The other thing I'm remembered for</i>

27
00:02:22,172 --> 00:02:25,938
<i>is what happened on 1st August, 1976,</i>

28
00:02:26,012 --> 00:02:27,537
<i>when I was chasing him</i>

29
00:02:27,612 --> 00:02:29,694
<i>like an asshole.</i>

30
00:03:00,212 --> 00:03:01,657
Trauma trolley, please.

31
00:03:01,732 --> 00:03:04,133
Hello, I think the racetrack
telephoned ahead that I was coming.

32
00:03:04,212 --> 00:03:05,657
Hunt. James Hunt.

33
00:03:10,732 --> 00:03:13,815
What's the matter? No one ever seen
a spot of blood before?

34
00:03:14,172 --> 00:03:16,823
- Are you all right?
- Absolutely fine.

35
00:03:19,972 --> 00:03:21,861
We all thought
you'd been in an accident.

36
00:03:21,972 --> 00:03:23,019
I have.

37
00:03:23,172 --> 00:03:26,335
If you call a friendly disagreement
with another driver an accident.

38
00:03:32,492 --> 00:03:34,256
What did you disagree about?

39
00:03:34,332 --> 00:03:35,902
It's none of your business.

40
00:03:36,012 --> 00:03:38,014
Sorry.

41
00:03:39,012 --> 00:03:40,377
His wife.

42
00:03:42,412 --> 00:03:44,938
That's going to need a couple
of stitches. It's a nasty cut.

43
00:03:45,012 --> 00:03:48,095
It was a nasty blow.
Done with a bloody crowbar.

44
00:03:49,012 --> 00:03:51,777
- Why? What did you do?
- Nothing.

45
00:03:52,372 --> 00:03:54,613
Only what she asked me to do.

46
00:03:56,852 --> 00:03:58,377
Which was...

47
00:03:59,012 --> 00:04:01,538
I'd be happy to show you, if you like.

48
00:04:04,732 --> 00:04:07,019
Oh! Sorry.

49
00:04:07,132 --> 00:04:10,932
<i>I have a theory
why women like racing drivers.</i>

50
00:04:11,292 --> 00:04:13,613
<i>It's not because
they respect what we do,</i>

51
00:04:13,692 --> 00:04:16,502
<i>driving round and round in circles.</i>

52
00:04:16,572 --> 00:04:19,143
<i>Mostly they think that's pathetic,
and they're probably right.</i>

53
00:04:20,372 --> 00:04:22,454
<i>It's our closeness to death.</i>

54
00:04:23,292 --> 00:04:26,978
<i>You see, the closer you are to death,
the more alive you feel.</i>

55
00:04:27,052 --> 00:04:30,056
<i>The more alive you are.
And they can see that in you.</i>

56
00:04:30,132 --> 00:04:32,055
<i>They feel that in you.</i>

57
00:04:33,212 --> 00:04:35,453
<i>My name is James Hunt.</i>

58
00:04:35,572 --> 00:04:37,574
<i>My father is a stockbroker,</i>

59
00:04:37,612 --> 00:04:41,219
<i>my sister is a barrister
and my brother is an accountant.</i>

60
00:04:42,292 --> 00:04:43,737
<i>And I...</i>

61
00:04:44,252 --> 00:04:45,902
<i>Well, I do this.</i>

62
00:04:47,412 --> 00:04:48,937
<i>It's a wonderful way to live.</i>

63
00:04:49,092 --> 00:04:51,140
<i>It's the only way to drive.</i>

64
00:04:52,092 --> 00:04:54,493
<i>As if each day is your last.</i>

65
00:05:03,772 --> 00:05:06,252
I've never been to a Grand Prix before.

66
00:05:06,332 --> 00:05:08,175
Oh, you still haven't.

67
00:05:08,252 --> 00:05:10,778
- This is Formula 3.
- What's that?

68
00:05:11,612 --> 00:05:13,853
It's a lower division,

69
00:05:13,932 --> 00:05:16,458
where idiots like me mess about

70
00:05:16,852 --> 00:05:19,537
in the hope of being talent-spotted
to race in Formula 1.

71
00:05:19,612 --> 00:05:21,614
- You look disappointed.
- No.

72
00:05:22,092 --> 00:05:25,301
Ah. You only slept with me
because you thought I was famous.

73
00:05:25,372 --> 00:05:26,942
That's not true.

74
00:05:27,612 --> 00:05:29,614
Don't worry. I will be one day.

75
00:05:29,692 --> 00:05:31,296
Morning, everyone.

76
00:05:31,332 --> 00:05:32,936
- This is Nursie.
- Gemma.

77
00:05:33,612 --> 00:05:36,456
Nursie, this is Bubbles Horsley,
team manager.

78
00:05:36,532 --> 00:05:37,613
How do you do?

79
00:05:38,012 --> 00:05:39,776
- Bubbles?
- Yeah.

80
00:05:39,812 --> 00:05:42,816
- Doc Postlethwaite, our designer.
- How do you do?

81
00:05:42,892 --> 00:05:46,817
And Alexander, Lord Hesketh,
the team's owner.

82
00:05:47,852 --> 00:05:49,342
How do you do?

83
00:05:50,172 --> 00:05:51,662
Fine, thanks.

84
00:05:51,692 --> 00:05:53,581
<i>Well done, Superstar.</i>

85
00:05:53,652 --> 00:05:56,178
- That's the car?
- Yep, that's her.

86
00:05:56,292 --> 00:05:58,021
Lotus 59.

87
00:05:58,132 --> 00:06:00,863
1,000cc Cosworth MAE engine.

88
00:06:00,972 --> 00:06:03,816
She's no beauty,
but goes like the clappers.

89
00:06:10,372 --> 00:06:12,420
Nothing to be worried about.
Does it before every race.

90
00:06:12,492 --> 00:06:14,574
Good sign, actually. Means he's stoked.

91
00:06:14,652 --> 00:06:18,862
<i>AH Formula 3 cars
to the assembly area now, please.</i>

92
00:06:30,572 --> 00:06:33,781
<i>...drivers please bring them
to the scrutineering bay now.</i>

93
00:06:34,172 --> 00:06:35,742
All right, Superstar?

94
00:06:35,852 --> 00:06:37,536
Never better, patron.

95
00:06:37,572 --> 00:06:40,052
- Have a gargle with this.
- Thank you.

96
00:06:41,532 --> 00:06:42,943
Quick toke of this.

97
00:06:43,852 --> 00:06:46,742
<i>At Crystal Palace today,
James Hunt's on pole,</i>

98
00:06:47,572 --> 00:06:50,860
<i>with Austrian newcomer
Niki Lauda alongside him</i>

99
00:06:50,892 --> 00:06:53,543
<i>and Dave Walker completing Row 1.</i>

100
00:06:53,612 --> 00:06:56,092
<i>Row 2 is Mike Beuttler and Dave Morgan,</i>

101
00:06:56,212 --> 00:06:59,102
<i>- with Tony Trimmer and Gerry Birrell.
- Who's that?</i>

102
00:06:59,452 --> 00:07:00,977
<i>He's new.</i>

103
00:07:01,452 --> 00:07:04,296
- Some German.
- Austrian.

104
00:07:04,372 --> 00:07:07,455
He's been here since 5:00 am,
walking the track.

105
00:07:07,532 --> 00:07:09,899
You might actually
have to concentrate today, James.

106
00:07:09,972 --> 00:07:11,576
You'll need these.

107
00:07:12,252 --> 00:07:14,823
<i>-  Okay, start her up.</i>

108
00:07:14,892 --> 00:07:17,372
Ah! What music!

109
00:07:17,412 --> 00:07:18,902
They could never have imagined it,

110
00:07:18,972 --> 00:07:21,259
those pioneers
who invented the automobile,

111
00:07:21,372 --> 00:07:25,582
that it would possess us like this,
in our imaginations, in our dreams.

112
00:07:26,332 --> 00:07:28,619
Nursie, men love women,

113
00:07:28,732 --> 00:07:30,496
but even more than that,

114
00:07:30,572 --> 00:07:33,894
men love cars.

115
00:07:41,012 --> 00:07:44,175
- Come on, James!
- James! Come on, James!

116
00:07:45,172 --> 00:07:46,583
Go, James!

117
00:07:54,252 --> 00:07:55,413
<i>Hunt's still in the lead,</i>

118
00:07:55,492 --> 00:07:57,654
<i>but Niki Lauda is right on his tail.</i>

119
00:08:06,452 --> 00:08:09,296
<i>Hunt and Lauda are
proving to be in a class of their own.</i>

120
00:08:09,332 --> 00:08:10,936
<i>They're leaving the pack far behind.</i>

121
00:08:11,332 --> 00:08:12,936
<i>Herr Red Devil's on his tail.</i>

122
00:08:19,052 --> 00:08:21,054
<i>Lauda takes a look down the inside...</i>

123
00:08:22,692 --> 00:08:24,456
<i>...and he's sold him a dummy!</i>

124
00:08:27,972 --> 00:08:29,974
<i>Lauda is through! He's in the lead!</i>

125
00:08:30,812 --> 00:08:33,213
<i>Hunt will be determined
to make up for that mistake.</i>

126
00:08:39,972 --> 00:08:41,542
<i>Hunt's in Lauda's slipstream.</i>

127
00:08:41,652 --> 00:08:43,620
<i>Lauda's not leaving any gap.</i>

128
00:08:48,732 --> 00:08:52,737
<i>The Lotus goes for the inside.
It's an aggressive move from Hunt.</i>

129
00:08:56,812 --> 00:08:58,735
<i>Oh! There's contact!</i>

130
00:09:05,492 --> 00:09:08,735
<i>The leaders have spun out!
Lauda's facing the wrong way!</i>

131
00:09:09,332 --> 00:09:11,699
<i>The back marker's gone through.</i>

132
00:09:12,052 --> 00:09:13,656
<i>You can see why Hunt's fellow drivers</i>

133
00:09:13,732 --> 00:09:15,573
<i>- call him "Hunt the Shunt".</i>

134
00:09:19,012 --> 00:09:20,013
Asshole!

135
00:09:20,092 --> 00:09:21,856
- Go on, James!
- The Kraut's out of it.

136
00:09:22,172 --> 00:09:24,095
<i>Lauda is clearly furious.</i>

137
00:09:24,172 --> 00:09:27,619
<i>There's every reason
to expect sharp words in the pits.</i>

138
00:09:27,692 --> 00:09:29,581
<i>It's gonna be victory for Hunt.</i>

139
00:09:29,692 --> 00:09:33,014
<i>It's gonna be an ignominious defeat
for Niki Lauda.</i>

140
00:09:37,732 --> 00:09:41,623
<i>So James Hunt scores his
third major Formula 3 win of the season</i>

141
00:09:41,692 --> 00:09:42,932
<i>here at Crystal Palace,</i>

142
00:09:43,052 --> 00:09:45,783
<i>after a desperate battle
with Niki Lauda.</i>

143
00:09:45,852 --> 00:09:47,581
<i>Lauda was unable to restart</i>

144
00:09:47,692 --> 00:09:50,423
<i>after Hunt's aggressive move
caused them both to spin out</i>

145
00:09:50,532 --> 00:09:51,693
<i>in the last lap of the race.</i>

146
00:09:53,132 --> 00:09:54,812
Hard luck.
Better luck next time.

147
00:09:55,372 --> 00:09:56,897
Hey, asshole.

148
00:09:57,972 --> 00:10:00,134
That was my line. I had that corner.

149
00:10:00,212 --> 00:10:03,455
Do you mean the one that you spun out of
and finished facing the other way?

150
00:10:03,572 --> 00:10:05,893
I think that corner had you.

151
00:10:05,972 --> 00:10:08,498
That move was total suicide.
What if I hadn't braked?

152
00:10:08,572 --> 00:10:11,416
- We'd have crashed.
- But we didn't, did we?

153
00:10:11,452 --> 00:10:13,420
Thanks to your impeccable
survival instincts.

154
00:10:15,572 --> 00:10:17,415
Fuck you. What's your name?

155
00:10:19,052 --> 00:10:23,421
James Simon Wallis Hunt.
Remember it, my little Jerry friend.

156
00:10:23,772 --> 00:10:25,422
<i>Jawohl. Remember ze name.</i>

157
00:10:25,452 --> 00:10:28,262
And it's very simple. Hunt.
It rhymes with...

158
00:10:28,292 --> 00:10:29,418
...cunt.

159
00:10:29,492 --> 00:10:31,972
A word that happens
to describe you perfectly!

160
00:10:32,572 --> 00:10:34,017
Who was that?

161
00:10:34,092 --> 00:10:36,254
I've no idea.
He looks like a rat, doesn't he?

162
00:10:38,572 --> 00:10:40,017
<i>In my home town, Vienna,</i>

163
00:10:40,452 --> 00:10:43,774
<i>my family is famous
for one thing - business.</i>

164
00:10:44,332 --> 00:10:46,619
<i>My grandfather was a businessman,</i>

165
00:10:47,092 --> 00:10:48,537
<i>my father, too.</i>

166
00:10:49,332 --> 00:10:52,461
<i>So when they heard I wanted
to race cars for a living,</i>

167
00:10:52,532 --> 00:10:54,341
<i>they had a few things to say.</i>

168
00:11:19,452 --> 00:11:20,817
<i>Gut.</i>

169
00:11:41,492 --> 00:11:43,494
<i>So if my family
wasn't going to help me,</i>

170
00:11:43,652 --> 00:11:47,338
<i>I decided to risk everything
and take out a loan myself.</i>

171
00:11:47,412 --> 00:11:50,382
<i>I found a Formula 1 team
with an okay car</i>

172
00:11:50,492 --> 00:11:52,540
<i>and an owner who had run out of money</i>

173
00:11:52,652 --> 00:11:54,814
<i>and was willing to accept my terms.</i>

174
00:11:55,212 --> 00:11:56,896
<i>And so,
ladies and gentlemen,</i>

175
00:11:57,012 --> 00:11:58,776
I'm delighted to say

176
00:11:58,852 --> 00:12:02,379
that the winner of the Guild of Motoring
Writers Award Driver of the Year...

177
00:12:03,572 --> 00:12:04,573
is James Hunt.

178
00:12:08,492 --> 00:12:09,937
Superb news!

179
00:12:10,692 --> 00:12:12,854
- Well done, James.
- Superstar!

180
00:12:13,012 --> 00:12:14,457
Fantastic!

181
00:12:16,012 --> 00:12:18,219
- Well done. Congratulations.
- Thank you so much.

182
00:12:18,372 --> 00:12:19,453
Yes!

183
00:12:19,532 --> 00:12:20,863
Erm...

184
00:12:20,892 --> 00:12:23,702
You know, my parents
always wanted me to be a doctor...

185
00:12:23,852 --> 00:12:25,900
...or a stockbroker or something.

186
00:12:26,012 --> 00:12:27,696
They gave me the first-class education,

187
00:12:27,772 --> 00:12:29,854
but, well, that all went terribly wrong

188
00:12:29,932 --> 00:12:31,972
and I ended up with you lot.

189
00:12:34,772 --> 00:12:36,292
Thank you. I need it more than you do.

190
00:12:38,412 --> 00:12:42,098
I mean, I have a hot head,
an inability to tolerate discipline.

191
00:12:42,212 --> 00:12:43,577
- Yes!
- Very true.

192
00:12:44,292 --> 00:12:46,135
I fall out with people left and right.

193
00:12:46,772 --> 00:12:49,821
The only creatures I've ever really
loved or have treated honourably

194
00:12:49,892 --> 00:12:51,894
are budgerigars.

195
00:12:53,212 --> 00:12:57,217
So in any normal area of life I'd be...
or I am, a total liability.

196
00:12:57,572 --> 00:12:59,892
The only thing I've got going for me
is I'm quick in a car.

197
00:13:00,052 --> 00:13:02,012
So, thank you for this
and for acknowledging that.

198
00:13:02,052 --> 00:13:03,497
I'm going to give it to my father

199
00:13:03,572 --> 00:13:05,336
and tell him to put it
on the mantelpiece

200
00:13:05,412 --> 00:13:07,733
and imagine it's a first-class degree
in medicine.

201
00:13:23,092 --> 00:13:24,935
Well done, Superstar.

202
00:13:24,972 --> 00:13:27,578
Another season like that
and I'll move you up to the big time.

203
00:13:27,692 --> 00:13:29,262
Come on, you don't think I'm ready now?

204
00:13:29,332 --> 00:13:32,700
You are. I'm not.
I've got to find you a car first.

205
00:13:32,852 --> 00:13:35,173
Well, go on, then. Chop-chop.

206
00:13:35,252 --> 00:13:37,539
Don't wait too long. You don't want him
to do what Lauda just did.

207
00:13:37,612 --> 00:13:40,616
- Why? What did he do?
- Got himself a drive with BRM.

208
00:13:40,652 --> 00:13:42,859
Well, how the hell did he do that?
He's a nobody.

209
00:13:42,932 --> 00:13:44,377
He's never won a bloody thing.

210
00:13:44,452 --> 00:13:46,375
Apparently, took out a loan
and bought his way in

211
00:13:46,452 --> 00:13:48,102
with two million Austrian schillings.

212
00:13:48,172 --> 00:13:49,617
Jesus.

213
00:14:09,132 --> 00:14:12,181
Niki Lauda.
Here for pre-season testing. BRM?

214
00:14:13,692 --> 00:14:16,502
Sign the release form.
I'll let them know you're here.

215
00:14:28,252 --> 00:14:29,777
- Mr Stanley.
- Good morning.

216
00:14:29,812 --> 00:14:32,736
- Good morning.
- Good morning. Clay!

217
00:14:32,812 --> 00:14:35,497
Let me introduce you
to our number-one driver,

218
00:14:35,572 --> 00:14:37,574
Clay Regazzoni.

219
00:14:38,972 --> 00:14:40,701
- How are you?
- Good.

220
00:14:41,452 --> 00:14:44,456
- Pleasure.
- And these are your mechanics.

221
00:14:45,012 --> 00:14:49,461
They're reporting exclusively to you,
as per contract.

222
00:14:49,532 --> 00:14:51,296
Pleasure. Do you wanna see the car?

223
00:14:51,372 --> 00:14:52,817
Sure.

224
00:14:54,852 --> 00:14:56,263
Hello.

225
00:15:01,292 --> 00:15:03,738
There she is. P160.

226
00:15:04,612 --> 00:15:07,138
- Same as Regazzoni's?
- Identical in every detail.

227
00:15:08,092 --> 00:15:09,582
How much does she weigh?

228
00:15:09,732 --> 00:15:12,338
- 600 kilos.
- But that's crazy.

229
00:15:12,532 --> 00:15:15,138
- Why so heavy?
- It's a V12 engine.

230
00:15:15,212 --> 00:15:18,341
That lump weighs 190K on its own.

231
00:15:18,412 --> 00:15:20,335
Okay.

232
00:15:20,412 --> 00:15:22,699
What horsepower are you getting? 490?

233
00:15:22,772 --> 00:15:25,173
- No, no, 450.
- Well, it's not enough.

234
00:15:25,252 --> 00:15:26,663
It needs to be 500,

235
00:15:26,732 --> 00:15:28,416
and the engine
needs to be 20 kilo lighter.

236
00:15:28,492 --> 00:15:29,732
We already tried.

237
00:15:29,812 --> 00:15:30,973
- Tried what?
- Everything.

238
00:15:31,172 --> 00:15:32,692
We replaced the entire exhaust system.

239
00:15:32,732 --> 00:15:36,020
- Barely made a difference.
- Are you using magnesium parts?

240
00:15:49,052 --> 00:15:50,497
Now the engine block.

241
00:15:50,572 --> 00:15:53,303
Any mounting or fixing plates,
strip it out also.

242
00:15:53,612 --> 00:15:56,695
When you've done that,
we have to look at the aerodynamics,

243
00:15:56,772 --> 00:15:58,536
front and rear wing.

244
00:16:15,972 --> 00:16:18,054
Okay, thank you. Good night.

245
00:16:38,012 --> 00:16:39,457
What was Regazzoni's time?

246
00:16:41,332 --> 00:16:42,743
1253.

247
00:16:43,092 --> 00:16:45,936
Okay, now put him in my car,
and he'll go round two seconds faster.

248
00:16:46,012 --> 00:16:49,061
- Well, that's impossible.
-  No chance.

249
00:16:52,092 --> 00:16:54,379
We've been working on it all night.

250
00:16:54,452 --> 00:16:56,500
Put Regazzoni in the car.
See what happens.

251
00:16:56,572 --> 00:16:58,415
I don't understand.
Why am I supposed to do this?

252
00:16:58,492 --> 00:17:00,852
I don't know, Clay.
He just wants you to take it for a spin.

253
00:17:03,692 --> 00:17:05,217
Gloves, please.

254
00:17:05,292 --> 00:17:06,737
'fanculo.

255
00:17:49,932 --> 00:17:52,981
- I would say we push it a bit...
- All right.

256
00:17:53,052 --> 00:17:55,054
What did you do to the car?

257
00:17:55,132 --> 00:17:58,659
That's information I will share with you
under certain conditions only.

258
00:17:58,892 --> 00:18:00,337
Go on.

259
00:18:01,412 --> 00:18:03,096
A guaranteed place in the team,

260
00:18:03,452 --> 00:18:05,972
and a paid contract on equal terms
with Regazzoni for two years.

261
00:18:07,212 --> 00:18:08,816
Are you crazy?

262
00:18:08,932 --> 00:18:12,459
Clay's a senior figure in Formula 1.
You're just a rookie.

263
00:18:12,812 --> 00:18:15,372
Well, the only reason we took you on
is because you're paying us.

264
00:18:15,652 --> 00:18:18,895
Well, as of now, if you want me to stay,
we rip up the contract.

265
00:18:18,972 --> 00:18:21,703
- I don't pay you a cent.
- That's outrageous!

266
00:18:22,212 --> 00:18:24,294
Was he quicker in my car?

267
00:18:25,012 --> 00:18:27,014
He was, wasn't he?

268
00:18:27,732 --> 00:18:29,973
Did he go two seconds faster?

269
00:18:33,612 --> 00:18:35,057
2.3.

270
00:18:37,772 --> 00:18:39,900
So, have a think,

271
00:18:40,532 --> 00:18:42,773
work out your priorities
and get back to me.

272
00:18:57,772 --> 00:18:59,183
Hey, Niki.

273
00:19:01,572 --> 00:19:04,462
I know what you're going to say,
that it's none of my business.

274
00:19:04,572 --> 00:19:05,573
What?

275
00:19:06,972 --> 00:19:10,294
If it's the track manager
you're taking on your date tonight...

276
00:19:11,332 --> 00:19:12,902
It's none of your business.

277
00:19:12,972 --> 00:19:16,738
Okay, but if you want my advice,
I'd let this one go.

278
00:19:18,092 --> 00:19:21,733
I'm not questioning your taste.
She is a great girl, but...

279
00:19:23,372 --> 00:19:27,263
Agnes's last boyfriend
was a British Formula 2 driver

280
00:19:27,332 --> 00:19:29,653
who has a reputation for two things.

281
00:19:29,732 --> 00:19:32,417
For being a little crazy on the track,

282
00:19:32,572 --> 00:19:36,736
and for going all night and all day
and all night again in bed.

283
00:19:36,852 --> 00:19:40,299
He's a good driver,
but an immortal fuck, apparently.

284
00:19:40,372 --> 00:19:43,342
I don't know about you, but
that's not an act I'd like to follow.

285
00:19:46,652 --> 00:19:48,734
But if that doesn't bother you...

286
00:19:50,652 --> 00:19:53,622
What's his name, the driver?

287
00:19:53,852 --> 00:19:55,377
Hunt. James Hunt.

288
00:19:59,492 --> 00:20:02,939
You see, you share information
and I share information.

289
00:20:04,292 --> 00:20:06,499
That's what teammates are for.

290
00:20:16,732 --> 00:20:18,222
<i>Where the hell are we going?</i>

291
00:20:18,292 --> 00:20:20,579
<i>I promise
it'll be worth it.</i>

292
00:20:20,652 --> 00:20:22,097
<i>Just keep them closed.</i>

293
00:20:22,532 --> 00:20:23,977
Wait for it.

294
00:20:24,812 --> 00:20:26,621
Wait for it.

295
00:20:29,972 --> 00:20:32,418
There. What do you say?

296
00:20:32,532 --> 00:20:34,102
She's Formula 1.

297
00:20:34,532 --> 00:20:36,216
Yes, she is, Superstar.

298
00:20:36,652 --> 00:20:39,462
Your brother and I got together
with the bean counters.

299
00:20:39,532 --> 00:20:40,943
And since the economics of F1

300
00:20:41,012 --> 00:20:44,573
are not so significantly different
to the economics of Formula 2,

301
00:20:44,652 --> 00:20:47,053
well, we thought if we were
going to be losing money,

302
00:20:47,172 --> 00:20:50,221
we might as well be doing it on
the big roulette table in Formula 1.

303
00:20:50,292 --> 00:20:53,614
You fat, little, inbred beauty.
Come here.

304
00:20:57,932 --> 00:21:01,254
Actually, credit where it's due,
we got the idea from Niki.

305
00:21:01,532 --> 00:21:03,455
<i>- Who?
-  Lauda.</i>

306
00:21:03,532 --> 00:21:06,297
Bought his way in, rather than
mess about in the lower divisions.

307
00:21:06,372 --> 00:21:07,942
I thought, "Bloody hell, he's right."

308
00:21:08,172 --> 00:21:11,574
No sponsorship, Superstar.
I hope you approve.

309
00:21:11,652 --> 00:21:15,657
No vulgar logos
for cigarettes or condoms.

310
00:21:16,212 --> 00:21:18,260
Just plain white with the flags. Ooh!

311
00:21:18,692 --> 00:21:21,662
And racing overalls which read,

312
00:21:22,852 --> 00:21:25,378
"Sex. Breakfast of champions."

313
00:21:28,132 --> 00:21:29,941
So, when do we start?

314
00:21:30,892 --> 00:21:33,099
- Soon as you're ready.
- Ready?

315
00:21:33,412 --> 00:21:35,983
I've been waiting for this
my whole life.

316
00:21:44,972 --> 00:21:46,940
- Hi, welcome to Watkins Glen.
- Hello!

317
00:21:47,012 --> 00:21:48,776
<i>When the season started,
people wondered</i>

318
00:21:49,092 --> 00:21:51,902
<i>whether Lord Hesketh and his team
of upper-class enthusiasts</i>

319
00:21:52,252 --> 00:21:56,655
<i>were bringing glamour
to the racing community, or just comedy.</i>

320
00:21:56,732 --> 00:21:58,814
Certainly, it was the first time
anyone had seen

321
00:21:58,892 --> 00:22:02,453
a butler serving oysters and caviar
in the pits.

322
00:22:02,532 --> 00:22:05,297
But they have made quite an impact.

323
00:22:05,372 --> 00:22:08,535
Sixth in France, fourth in Britain
and third in Holland.

324
00:22:08,612 --> 00:22:12,219
<i>AH drivers on the track,
caution flags are out.</i>

325
00:22:12,292 --> 00:22:14,374
<i>A severe crash at the Esses.</i>

326
00:22:14,692 --> 00:22:16,501
<i>Red flag.
There is a car off the track.</i>

327
00:22:16,572 --> 00:22:18,256
And reports are reaching me

328
00:22:18,332 --> 00:22:20,539
that there has been
a serious accident in qualifying.

329
00:22:20,892 --> 00:22:23,418
Er, the identity of the driver we don't
currently have at the moment,

330
00:22:23,492 --> 00:22:25,699
but, as you can tell
from all the activity

331
00:22:25,812 --> 00:22:27,416
going on behind me towards the track,

332
00:22:27,492 --> 00:22:29,893
it is clearly a grave incident indeed.

333
00:22:29,972 --> 00:22:31,383
We will, of course,
have more information for you

334
00:22:31,452 --> 00:22:32,499
as and when we get it,

335
00:22:32,612 --> 00:22:36,617
but it is the sight and sound
of Formula 1 nobody likes to see.

336
00:22:40,612 --> 00:22:42,376
- Get your hands off me.
- Hey, come on.

337
00:22:52,532 --> 00:22:53,897
<i>Drivers of top stature</i>

338
00:22:53,972 --> 00:22:55,701
<i>we've lost just in the past four seasons</i>

339
00:22:55,772 --> 00:23:00,619
<i>have included Piers Courage,
Jochen Rindt,</i>

340
00:23:00,692 --> 00:23:03,980
<i>Jo Siffert, Roger Williamson</i>

341
00:23:04,052 --> 00:23:06,259
<i>and today, at Watkins Glen,</i>

342
00:23:06,332 --> 00:23:08,653
<i>Formula 1 has claimed another driver.</i>

343
00:23:09,252 --> 00:23:11,539
<i>The Tyrrell team
have withdrawn from the race.</i>

344
00:23:11,652 --> 00:23:14,303
<i>Their places on the grid
will be left empty.</i>

345
00:23:14,372 --> 00:23:16,818
- Terrible.
- They should cancel the race.

346
00:23:17,052 --> 00:23:18,577
Why?

347
00:23:18,892 --> 00:23:21,338
He made a mistake,
went into the corner too fast.

348
00:23:21,452 --> 00:23:22,863
It's his fault.

349
00:23:22,932 --> 00:23:24,821
- Is that right?
- It's obvious.

350
00:23:25,212 --> 00:23:26,941
Look at the tyre marks.

351
00:23:27,332 --> 00:23:30,575
So says the nobody
who had to pay for his own drive.

352
00:23:30,652 --> 00:23:32,332
How's that working out for you,
by the way?

353
00:23:32,532 --> 00:23:35,342
Fine. How is it at the back?

354
00:23:36,252 --> 00:23:38,334
Not planning on being there for long.

355
00:23:39,212 --> 00:23:40,623
<i>Ten minutes to the warm-up lap.</i>

356
00:23:40,812 --> 00:23:42,257
<i>Ten minutes.</i>

357
00:23:45,652 --> 00:23:47,017
Arsehole.

358
00:23:48,412 --> 00:23:51,700
<i>Heading into
the Grand Hotel hairpin, second gear.</i>

359
00:23:51,772 --> 00:23:52,773
Turn in hard,

360
00:23:52,852 --> 00:23:55,503
looking for late apex,
gentle with the bar.

361
00:23:57,252 --> 00:24:00,381
Heading into Portier, second gear,
clip the apex,

362
00:24:00,492 --> 00:24:04,053
light brake, stay in second,
looking for a good exit.

363
00:24:04,412 --> 00:24:06,460
Heading through the tunnel,
gradual right,

364
00:24:06,532 --> 00:24:09,502
up through third, fourth, fifth...

365
00:24:09,572 --> 00:24:11,574
ls Alexander round?

366
00:24:12,092 --> 00:24:14,698
Er, yes, he was.

367
00:24:14,772 --> 00:24:16,376
He went back to the house
to take a call.

368
00:24:16,452 --> 00:24:18,216
He'll be back shortly.

369
00:24:18,292 --> 00:24:20,454
He only wanted to show me
his pride and joy.

370
00:24:21,412 --> 00:24:24,143
Rhymes with "boy", if you ask me.

371
00:24:24,212 --> 00:24:26,021
And "toy".

372
00:24:26,092 --> 00:24:30,302
God, it's so flimsy
for something that costs so much.

373
00:24:30,372 --> 00:24:34,377
There's no comfort,
no protection, nothing.

374
00:24:34,452 --> 00:24:37,103
No, it's just a little coffin, really.

375
00:24:37,172 --> 00:24:40,221
Surrounded by high-octane fuel in here.

376
00:24:40,292 --> 00:24:43,216
Being driven round 170 miles per hour.

377
00:24:43,292 --> 00:24:46,455
To all intents and purposes,
this thing's a bomb on wheels.

378
00:24:47,612 --> 00:24:49,535
You're James, aren't you?

379
00:24:50,772 --> 00:24:52,262
Yes.

380
00:24:53,212 --> 00:24:54,941
You fit the description.

381
00:24:55,332 --> 00:24:56,743
Is that right?

382
00:24:57,972 --> 00:24:59,940
Suzy. Friend of Alex's.

383
00:25:00,052 --> 00:25:03,181
Yeah, yeah. I know exactly.

384
00:25:04,852 --> 00:25:06,342
What was the description?

385
00:25:06,412 --> 00:25:07,973
Mostly positive,
in terms of appearance.

386
00:25:08,012 --> 00:25:10,219
Negative only in terms of character.

387
00:25:10,732 --> 00:25:12,655
I've been told to avoid you.

388
00:25:13,052 --> 00:25:14,463
BY Whom?

389
00:25:14,892 --> 00:25:17,736
Alexander. He says you're a bad boy.

390
00:25:17,812 --> 00:25:20,099
Alexander doesn't know
what he's talking about.

391
00:25:20,172 --> 00:25:22,539
I was. I'm not any more.

392
00:25:22,612 --> 00:25:26,139
The new me is very professional.
Early to bed, early to rise.

393
00:25:26,212 --> 00:25:27,782
- All very dull.
- Hmm.

394
00:25:27,852 --> 00:25:29,217
But according to the team,

395
00:25:29,292 --> 00:25:31,973
"The best way to
keep beating the goose-stepper."

396
00:25:32,772 --> 00:25:34,297
Is that what you were doing
when I came in?

397
00:25:34,372 --> 00:25:37,342
Yes, visualisation techniques,
memorising the circuit,

398
00:25:37,412 --> 00:25:40,097
in this case Monaco, which is up next.

399
00:25:44,892 --> 00:25:48,055
Personally, I've always been a great
believer in getting there on the day,

400
00:25:48,132 --> 00:25:50,612
putting my foot down
and playing chicken with everyone else.

401
00:25:52,932 --> 00:25:54,377
But they don't want me
doing that any more.

402
00:25:54,452 --> 00:25:58,537
They want my body like a temple
and my mind like a monk.

403
00:25:59,212 --> 00:26:02,341
And what about your soul, your heart?

404
00:26:02,412 --> 00:26:04,574
Well, they've got ideas about that, too.

405
00:26:04,652 --> 00:26:07,178
They want me to stop messing around,
settle down,

406
00:26:07,252 --> 00:26:09,493
get married
with the next nice girl I meet.

407
00:26:09,572 --> 00:26:10,983
They think it would be good for me.

408
00:26:11,452 --> 00:26:13,454
Hmm. What do you think?

409
00:26:13,812 --> 00:26:17,134
It sounds fucking awful.

410
00:26:18,252 --> 00:26:20,619
But since they're right
about most things,

411
00:26:20,892 --> 00:26:23,543
- they're probably right about that, too.
- Hmm.

412
00:26:23,612 --> 00:26:26,013
You don't fancy getting married, do you?

413
00:26:51,412 --> 00:26:52,937
Suzy.

414
00:26:53,652 --> 00:26:55,063
Bravo!

415
00:26:55,412 --> 00:26:57,335
Hey, hey, hey!

416
00:27:00,892 --> 00:27:02,815
- What's going on with him?
- Nothing. Nothing.

417
00:27:03,172 --> 00:27:04,583
Didn't want to ruin your day.

418
00:27:05,172 --> 00:27:07,573
It's... It's the Kraut.

419
00:27:07,852 --> 00:27:09,422
What about him?

420
00:27:10,292 --> 00:27:12,135
He's just been signed by Ferrari.

421
00:27:12,212 --> 00:27:15,933
You're kidding me?
Jesus. How did that happen?

422
00:27:16,212 --> 00:27:17,702
Did he buy his way in there, too?

423
00:27:17,812 --> 00:27:23,376
Well, the old man took Regazzoni back
and he insisted on it, apparently.

424
00:27:23,452 --> 00:27:25,420
He says that Niki's a genius
setting up the cars.

425
00:27:44,732 --> 00:27:46,496
It's terrible. Drives like a pig.

426
00:27:47,332 --> 00:27:49,699
- Oh, you can't say that.
- Why not?

427
00:27:50,052 --> 00:27:52,100
- It's a Ferrari!
- It's a shitbox.

428
00:27:52,572 --> 00:27:55,940
It understeers like crazy and
the weight distribution is a disaster.

429
00:27:56,012 --> 00:27:59,061
It's amazing, all these facilities
and you make a piece of crap like this.

430
00:28:00,452 --> 00:28:01,817
Uh!

431
00:28:30,532 --> 00:28:33,695
"Ferrari family."
"Our good friend Clay Regazzoni."

432
00:28:33,772 --> 00:28:37,254
You are family and friend
to the commendatore as long as you win.

433
00:28:37,332 --> 00:28:38,743
The minute you don't, ciao, ciao.

434
00:28:39,052 --> 00:28:43,182
I totally understand. It's business.
I would do the same.

435
00:28:43,292 --> 00:28:46,216
But it isn't
just business, is it? What we do.

436
00:28:46,292 --> 00:28:48,374
It's passion, love.

437
00:28:48,452 --> 00:28:51,217
Which is why we are prepared
to risk our lives for it.

438
00:28:51,292 --> 00:28:52,339
Not me.

439
00:28:52,412 --> 00:28:55,133
If I had more talent and could earn
better money with something else,

440
00:28:55,292 --> 00:28:56,896
I would.

441
00:28:56,972 --> 00:29:00,579
How do you know you will
make money here? You haven't yet.

442
00:29:00,652 --> 00:29:02,973
Not yet, but I will.

443
00:29:03,652 --> 00:29:05,541
If you can, I can.

444
00:29:09,412 --> 00:29:11,255
You know, are you ever not an asshole?

445
00:29:12,612 --> 00:29:14,580
- Why am I an asshole?
- Well...

446
00:29:14,652 --> 00:29:16,177
You know, by now
I'm both quicker than you

447
00:29:16,252 --> 00:29:18,095
and better at setting up the car.

448
00:29:18,172 --> 00:29:19,973
You can't deal with it,
so you're the asshole.

449
00:29:20,012 --> 00:29:21,173
Screw you.

450
00:29:29,092 --> 00:29:32,301
I brought you along today because
you seem like a lonely kind of guy.

451
00:29:32,372 --> 00:29:34,261
I thought if I introduced you
to some nice people,

452
00:29:34,332 --> 00:29:36,141
that could rub off on you.

453
00:29:36,212 --> 00:29:38,863
Forget it. Make your own friends.

454
00:29:38,932 --> 00:29:41,617
Come on, Clay. I'm sorry.

455
00:30:17,132 --> 00:30:18,577
Are you leaving?

456
00:30:19,692 --> 00:30:21,103
Yes.

457
00:30:21,572 --> 00:30:23,252
Can you give me a lift
to the nearest town,

458
00:30:23,332 --> 00:30:24,777
anywhere with a train station?

459
00:30:26,572 --> 00:30:29,655
Sure. Trento's half an hour's drive.

460
00:30:30,292 --> 00:30:31,339
Get in.

461
00:30:42,692 --> 00:30:46,139
J1 Been another blue day
without you, girl

462
00:30:47,252 --> 00:30:50,779
J1 Been another sad summer song

463
00:30:52,532 --> 00:30:56,537
J1 I been thinking about you, girl,
all night long

464
00:30:58,492 --> 00:30:59,573
What are you doing?

465
00:30:59,972 --> 00:31:01,573
You hear that noise when you accelerate?

466
00:31:01,972 --> 00:31:04,259
- No.
- Your fan belt is loose.

467
00:31:04,372 --> 00:31:06,056
My What?

468
00:31:06,132 --> 00:31:08,533
And when you brake,
your foot goes all the way down,

469
00:31:08,612 --> 00:31:10,132
which means there's air in the system.

470
00:31:10,372 --> 00:31:12,943
- Anything else?
- No.

471
00:31:13,932 --> 00:31:16,697
Apart from
the rear brakes are worn out,

472
00:31:17,012 --> 00:31:18,423
the front right tyre's a bit soft,

473
00:31:18,492 --> 00:31:20,221
which explains
why you're weaving so much.

474
00:31:20,292 --> 00:31:22,772
Hmm. How can you tell?

475
00:31:23,132 --> 00:31:25,100
- My ass.
- Sorry?

476
00:31:25,252 --> 00:31:27,141
God gave me an okay mind,

477
00:31:27,212 --> 00:31:29,943
but a really good ass,
which can feel everything in a car.

478
00:31:30,252 --> 00:31:32,493
You don't know what
you're talking about. This car is fine.

479
00:31:32,572 --> 00:31:35,303
- I just had a service a week ago.
- Not a good one.

480
00:31:35,372 --> 00:31:38,023
Yes, a very good one, very expensive.

481
00:31:38,572 --> 00:31:40,654
This car is as good as new. Relax.

482
00:31:47,972 --> 00:31:49,497
Not in a hurry, are you?

483
00:31:49,572 --> 00:31:51,256
No. As long as I'm back

484
00:31:51,332 --> 00:31:52,663
in Maranello Monday morning.

485
00:31:55,092 --> 00:31:56,332
Ja.

486
00:31:56,412 --> 00:31:58,574
- Marlene.
- Niki.

487
00:33:05,292 --> 00:33:07,863
<i>Mi scusi... Tu sei Niki Lauda?</i>

488
00:33:08,972 --> 00:33:10,940
Yes.

489
00:33:19,852 --> 00:33:21,263
- Actually, we do, yeah.
- Okay.

490
00:33:21,332 --> 00:33:22,538
It's my honour, Niki, please.

491
00:33:22,612 --> 00:33:24,853
- Thank you.
- My car is your car.

492
00:33:24,972 --> 00:33:28,693
On one condition, though.
It's a piece of shit. It's dog shit.

493
00:33:28,772 --> 00:33:31,855
But if you drive it,
you make my life, Niki, eh?

494
00:33:44,692 --> 00:33:46,820
- Niki Lauda!
- Niki Lauda, Niki Lauda!

495
00:33:48,732 --> 00:33:51,053
Will someone please tell me
what's going on?

496
00:33:51,132 --> 00:33:52,577
Who are you? Should I know you?

497
00:33:52,652 --> 00:33:54,142
What, you don't know?

498
00:33:54,732 --> 00:33:58,657
He's Niki Lauda, Formula 1 driver,
and he just signed with Ferrari.

499
00:33:58,732 --> 00:34:00,222
- Him?
- Yes.

500
00:34:00,332 --> 00:34:02,539
- Impossible.
- Why?

501
00:34:02,652 --> 00:34:07,180
Well, you know, Formula 1 drivers,
they have long hair, are sexy,

502
00:34:07,212 --> 00:34:08,657
their shirts are open to here.

503
00:34:08,732 --> 00:34:10,416
- Thank you.
- Yes.

504
00:34:10,492 --> 00:34:13,894
Anyway, look at the way he's driving,
like an old man.

505
00:34:18,172 --> 00:34:19,652
There's no need to drive fast.

506
00:34:19,932 --> 00:34:21,934
It just increases
the percentage of risk.

507
00:34:22,892 --> 00:34:24,493
We're not in a hurry.
I'm not being paid.

508
00:34:25,092 --> 00:34:27,857
Right now,
with zero incentive or reward,

509
00:34:27,932 --> 00:34:29,696
why would I drive fast?

510
00:34:31,532 --> 00:34:33,534
Because I'm asking you to.

511
00:34:39,052 --> 00:34:40,383
Ja.

512
00:35:37,412 --> 00:35:39,052
<i>This is an incredible battle</i>

513
00:35:39,092 --> 00:35:41,493
<i>between Niki Lauda in the red Ferrari</i>

514
00:35:41,572 --> 00:35:44,098
<i>and James Hunt in the white Hesketh.</i>

515
00:35:45,212 --> 00:35:46,702
...the challenge of Niki Lauda...

516
00:35:46,772 --> 00:35:48,262
<i>Lauda attacking Hunt.</i>

517
00:35:48,292 --> 00:35:50,101
<i>Lauda gets through on the inside.</i>

518
00:35:50,212 --> 00:35:51,737
<i>Goes wide at the exit.</i>

519
00:35:51,932 --> 00:35:53,422
<i>Hunt is past again.</i>

520
00:35:53,452 --> 00:35:56,535
<i>Once more
Lauda tries to sneak up the inside.</i>

521
00:35:56,612 --> 00:36:00,617
<i>They're absolutely side by side,
wheel to wheel.</i>

522
00:36:00,692 --> 00:36:04,742
<i>So evenly matched. Fantastic battle
between these two great drivers.</i>

523
00:36:04,772 --> 00:36:07,139
<i>Hunt is now ahead once more.</i>

524
00:36:08,612 --> 00:36:13,254
<i>But Lauda's coming back again now.
Lauda once more sneaks up the inside.</i>

525
00:36:13,292 --> 00:36:15,772
<i>And again he runs wide.
Again the Hesketh...</i>

526
00:36:15,932 --> 00:36:19,095
- Suzy, we're ready, come on.
- Just... Just one second.

527
00:36:19,972 --> 00:36:22,623
- Can we go, yeah?
- Okay, yeah.

528
00:36:23,372 --> 00:36:26,137
<i>We're in the closing laps
of this race here at Watkins Glen.</i>

529
00:36:26,212 --> 00:36:27,213
<i>They come down the hill.</i>

530
00:36:28,932 --> 00:36:30,582
<i>And Hunt's got a problem!</i>

531
00:36:30,652 --> 00:36:33,098
<i>Hunt pulls across to the left.</i>

532
00:36:33,132 --> 00:36:35,976
Lauda goes ahead on his own.

533
00:36:37,652 --> 00:36:40,132
<i>A sad end to a wonderful battle.</i>

534
00:36:40,252 --> 00:36:42,823
<i>Hunt pushing off the marshal.</i>

535
00:36:51,252 --> 00:36:55,337
<i>The chequered ﬂag
is waiting for Lauda and for Ferrari.</i>

536
00:36:56,772 --> 00:36:59,457
<i>The title going to Niki Lauda,</i>

537
00:36:59,492 --> 00:37:00,937
<i>who wins the race,</i>

538
00:37:01,012 --> 00:37:03,492
<i>who wins the World Championship.</i>

539
00:37:45,332 --> 00:37:48,302
- Congratulations.
- Thank you.

540
00:37:49,052 --> 00:37:50,497
Marlene.

541
00:37:52,092 --> 00:37:55,892
With a car like that, the rest of us
never really stood a chance, did we?

542
00:37:55,932 --> 00:37:58,902
Maybe the fact the car is so good
has something to do with me.

543
00:37:59,012 --> 00:38:01,902
Come on, Niki. You're in a Ferrari.
I'm in a Hesketh.

544
00:38:02,012 --> 00:38:03,901
Equal terms,
the way it was in Formula 3,

545
00:38:03,972 --> 00:38:06,418
- I'd beat you and you know it.
- Never.

546
00:38:06,532 --> 00:38:09,422
You might win one race, maybe two,
because you're aggressive.

547
00:38:09,652 --> 00:38:12,735
But in the long run, over the course
of a season, no chance.

548
00:38:12,852 --> 00:38:13,899
Right. Why's that?

549
00:38:14,172 --> 00:38:16,903
Because to be a champion,
it takes more than just being quick.

550
00:38:17,052 --> 00:38:18,736
- It's the whole picture.
- Oh.

551
00:38:18,812 --> 00:38:20,812
You're just a charger and a party guy.

552
00:38:20,852 --> 00:38:22,092
That's why everybody likes you.

553
00:38:22,692 --> 00:38:24,694
Try saying that
and tell me you're not jealous.

554
00:38:26,052 --> 00:38:28,737
Why would I be jealous? Think about it.

555
00:38:29,092 --> 00:38:31,174
All that affection, all those smiles

556
00:38:31,252 --> 00:38:33,061
- is a sign of disrespect.
- Oh.

557
00:38:33,092 --> 00:38:35,538
They don't fear you.
Whereas compare that to me.

558
00:38:35,612 --> 00:38:38,263
Yes, compared to you, whom no one likes.

559
00:38:38,372 --> 00:38:39,942
- Right.
- Not even his own teammates.

560
00:38:40,012 --> 00:38:42,777
Right. Because I'm a serious guy.

561
00:38:42,892 --> 00:38:45,293
I go to bed early,
I look after myself, look after my car.

562
00:38:45,412 --> 00:38:48,461
- Yes, you're very well-behaved.
- Go to work, kick ass.

563
00:38:48,572 --> 00:38:51,303
And then, after the race,
I go home instead of going to bars

564
00:38:51,412 --> 00:38:54,541
and talk all this bullshit
with all these assholes.

565
00:38:54,612 --> 00:38:56,455
Arseholes?

566
00:38:56,532 --> 00:38:58,978
You should go home more often, too.

567
00:39:02,292 --> 00:39:04,294
I heard you got married.

568
00:39:05,292 --> 00:39:06,896
Yes, I did.

569
00:39:08,452 --> 00:39:11,058
So where is she, this mysterious wife?

570
00:39:12,252 --> 00:39:14,254
- In New York, working.
- Oh.

571
00:39:15,652 --> 00:39:17,620
You know,
I've never seen you with her once.

572
00:39:17,652 --> 00:39:18,892
No?

573
00:39:21,252 --> 00:39:24,142
Well, maybe that's because
you're always at home,

574
00:39:24,212 --> 00:39:28,137
on your own, looking after yourself,
being a good little boy.

575
00:39:32,332 --> 00:39:33,663
Take a drink on me, James.

576
00:39:35,572 --> 00:39:38,178
Thank you, Niki. I might just have two.

577
00:39:49,532 --> 00:39:51,022
Right, Bubbles,

578
00:39:51,052 --> 00:39:54,181
whatever it takes to beat
that prick next year, just say it.

579
00:39:54,292 --> 00:39:55,703
Your word is my command.

580
00:39:55,812 --> 00:39:59,294
There are no lengths
to which I will not go. I mean it.

581
00:40:01,852 --> 00:40:03,695
What the hell's going on?

582
00:40:05,852 --> 00:40:08,458
Where is everybody? What's the matter?

583
00:40:14,052 --> 00:40:16,532
Do you know what the date is today?

584
00:40:16,612 --> 00:40:19,058
Yes, it's November, the 14th. Why?

585
00:40:19,492 --> 00:40:23,736
Do you have any idea
of the significance of that date?

586
00:40:25,052 --> 00:40:28,215
I don't know.
Time to start killing pheasants?

587
00:40:30,532 --> 00:40:33,297
Actually, it's the deadline
for securing sponsorship

588
00:40:33,372 --> 00:40:35,295
for the forthcoming Formula 1 season.

589
00:40:35,532 --> 00:40:36,977
Yes?

590
00:40:37,172 --> 00:40:40,142
Which elapsed at midnight last night,
and we didn't attract any.

591
00:40:40,532 --> 00:40:44,093
Well, so?
We aren't looking for sponsorship.

592
00:40:44,172 --> 00:40:46,459
Like you said, condoms and cigarettes,
vulgar, right?

593
00:40:48,412 --> 00:40:49,618
Right.

594
00:40:51,172 --> 00:40:53,539
Except we are, or were.

595
00:40:56,332 --> 00:40:58,778
I've made something of a miscalculation.

596
00:40:59,732 --> 00:41:03,214
The economics, Formula 1,
realities thereof.

597
00:41:04,612 --> 00:41:07,775
It turns out,
not like the lower divisions at all.

598
00:41:10,292 --> 00:41:12,021
What are you saying?

599
00:41:13,932 --> 00:41:16,412
I'm saying it's over, Superstar.

600
00:41:17,252 --> 00:41:20,779
The banks have stepped in,
started laying everyone off.

601
00:41:22,572 --> 00:41:24,973
Probably have to sell this place.

602
00:41:25,572 --> 00:41:27,574
Oh, Christ.

603
00:42:08,212 --> 00:42:11,978
I need a drive, Pete.
I need you to find me a drive.

604
00:42:12,412 --> 00:42:13,937
I mean, what about Lotus?

605
00:42:15,052 --> 00:42:16,497
You don't wanna know.

606
00:42:16,732 --> 00:42:19,463
<i>- Actually, I do.
- Okay. Uh...</i>

607
00:42:21,812 --> 00:42:23,814
They felt your reputation preceded you.

608
00:42:24,132 --> 00:42:25,816
And what does that mean?

609
00:42:27,452 --> 00:42:30,501
It's my other line.
Look, I'll get back to you.

610
00:42:32,412 --> 00:42:33,493
Peter Hunt.

611
00:42:33,852 --> 00:42:35,422
Fuck.

612
00:42:46,252 --> 00:42:47,697
Don't worry. Something will turn up.

613
00:42:56,492 --> 00:42:58,540
Doubt that will help in the meantime.

614
00:43:01,492 --> 00:43:04,143
Why don't we go away at the weekend?

615
00:43:04,212 --> 00:43:07,341
Skiing. Before I go back to New York.

616
00:43:10,972 --> 00:43:14,374
Talk to me, James.
Don't make a stranger of me.

617
00:43:14,492 --> 00:43:18,497
You know, Suzy,
only a stranger would invite me skiing

618
00:43:18,532 --> 00:43:20,978
when they know
I haven't got a fucking drive.

619
00:43:27,372 --> 00:43:29,136
I can't watch this.

620
00:43:29,892 --> 00:43:32,213
What were you hoping for anyway?

621
00:43:32,692 --> 00:43:34,979
A well-adjusted knight
in shining armour?

622
00:43:35,052 --> 00:43:36,975
No danger of that.

623
00:43:37,052 --> 00:43:39,339
- Let me give you some advice.
- I'm all ears.

624
00:43:39,412 --> 00:43:42,177
Don't go to men who are willing
to kill themselves driving in circles

625
00:43:42,252 --> 00:43:44,903
- looking for normality.
- I never expected normality.

626
00:43:45,012 --> 00:43:47,094
God knows I walked into this
with my eyes open.

627
00:43:47,172 --> 00:43:48,662
I just hoped I'd married someone

628
00:43:48,732 --> 00:43:51,815
who was half as impressive
on the inside as he is on the outside.

629
00:43:51,932 --> 00:43:53,696
At least there's something
behind the facade.

630
00:43:53,732 --> 00:43:55,939
- Oh, James.
- Fuck off to New York, dear.

631
00:43:57,092 --> 00:43:59,413
There must be a moisturiser
or an eye shadow somewhere

632
00:43:59,492 --> 00:44:01,256
that needs your vapid mush to flog it.

633
00:44:37,972 --> 00:44:39,417
<i>- Hello?
- Hi, James.</i>

634
00:44:39,452 --> 00:44:42,774
It's Peter. Something's up at McLaren.

635
00:44:43,372 --> 00:44:45,374
<i>- What have you heard?
- Nothing. Why?</i>

636
00:44:45,452 --> 00:44:47,978
I heard Emerson's off.
He's dumped them in it.

637
00:44:48,652 --> 00:44:50,734
Jesus. Get me in there, Pete.

638
00:44:50,812 --> 00:44:53,213
Say anything, just get me in that room.

639
00:44:58,132 --> 00:44:59,896
I'll come straight to the point.

640
00:44:59,972 --> 00:45:03,419
- Our esteemed lead driver...
- Fitti-fucking-paldi.

641
00:45:03,492 --> 00:45:05,733
...has ditched us for another team
at the last minute.

642
00:45:05,812 --> 00:45:08,133
- Coper-fucking-sucar.
- And we need a replacement.

643
00:45:08,172 --> 00:45:09,662
ASA-fucking-P.

644
00:45:10,652 --> 00:45:14,498
Fortunately, a few hands
have already gone up, good people.

645
00:45:15,332 --> 00:45:18,017
- Jacky Ickx.
- I'm quicker than Jacky.

646
00:45:18,452 --> 00:45:22,343
- But he's consistent, dependable.
- A grown-up.

647
00:45:22,412 --> 00:45:25,859
Right, and will he go for that gap
when no one else will?

648
00:45:25,972 --> 00:45:27,940
Will he put his life on the line
the day that it really matters?

649
00:45:28,252 --> 00:45:29,697
The sponsors like him.

650
00:45:30,172 --> 00:45:32,373
What do you want,
a driver or a brush salesman?

651
00:45:32,412 --> 00:45:34,332
- We wanna be successful.
- Yes, so do I.

652
00:45:34,612 --> 00:45:37,536
But that means beating Niki Lauda,
not being a show pony for sponsors.

653
00:45:37,612 --> 00:45:39,137
I heard about this thing with Niki.

654
00:45:39,172 --> 00:45:40,378
Everyone has.

655
00:45:41,652 --> 00:45:44,019
- You really think you can beat him?
- I'd beat him in a McLaren.

656
00:45:44,092 --> 00:45:47,380
It's the only car out there
as quick as the Ferrari.

657
00:45:47,692 --> 00:45:49,694
Which is why I'm here, begging.

658
00:45:50,172 --> 00:45:51,617
Look, I'll do whatever you ask.

659
00:45:51,692 --> 00:45:53,535
I'll put on a tie,
I'll smile for sponsors,

660
00:45:53,652 --> 00:45:55,541
say the right things.

661
00:45:55,852 --> 00:45:58,173
I can beat this guy, trust me.

662
00:45:59,012 --> 00:46:00,901
Just give me the drive.

663
00:46:01,612 --> 00:46:03,501
<i>Yeah.
Yeah, he can be a loose cannon.</i>

664
00:46:03,692 --> 00:46:05,296
And, yeah, he will drive you all mad,

665
00:46:05,372 --> 00:46:08,899
but in terms of raw talent
and right stuff,

666
00:46:09,012 --> 00:46:10,901
there is no better driver in the world.

667
00:46:11,292 --> 00:46:13,454
<i>He's the real thing, Teddy.</i>

668
00:46:13,572 --> 00:46:16,052
<i>- He's what we all came into this for.
- Mmm.</i>

669
00:46:16,172 --> 00:46:18,174
Nine days out of ten
you'll be pulling your hair out,

670
00:46:18,212 --> 00:46:21,375
but on that tenth day,
James will be unbeatable.

671
00:46:21,412 --> 00:46:23,414
And that is the day you will wish
you had him in your car.

672
00:46:23,692 --> 00:46:26,536
<i>You will never win the championship
with Jacky Ickx.</i>

673
00:46:26,892 --> 00:46:29,259
You just might with James.

674
00:46:51,412 --> 00:46:53,779
Welcome to Sao Paulo, Brazil,
and the Interlagos circuit

675
00:46:53,892 --> 00:46:57,533
for the first race
in the 1976 Formula 1 season,

676
00:46:57,772 --> 00:47:00,935
where the main news is that James Hunt
has qualified fastest,

677
00:47:01,012 --> 00:47:03,094
beating Niki Lauda's Ferrari
to pole position

678
00:47:03,212 --> 00:47:05,943
by just two hundredths of a second.

679
00:47:06,932 --> 00:47:08,536
New car.

680
00:47:09,372 --> 00:47:11,022
- I noticed.
- Pole position.

681
00:47:12,052 --> 00:47:13,383
I noticed that, too.

682
00:47:13,452 --> 00:47:15,898
Level playing field now,
my ratty little friend.

683
00:47:15,932 --> 00:47:19,539
Yeah. Let's see where we are
after lap one.

684
00:47:19,612 --> 00:47:22,422
Let's see where we are
in five races' time.

685
00:47:23,252 --> 00:47:25,380
Hunt has the pit lane pole position,

686
00:47:25,452 --> 00:47:28,262
which should give him the best chance
of outdragging Lauda's Ferrari.

687
00:47:29,292 --> 00:47:30,896
If ever there was a doubt about

688
00:47:30,972 --> 00:47:34,260
whether Lauda had
a serious challenger to this season,

689
00:47:34,292 --> 00:47:37,933
Hunt and his McLaren
have certainly given us the answer.

690
00:47:53,612 --> 00:47:55,137
<i>Here in South Africa,</i>

691
00:47:55,172 --> 00:47:57,174
<i>James Hunt is determined to make amends</i>

692
00:47:57,292 --> 00:48:00,296
<i>after that disastrous retirement
in Brazil.</i>

693
00:48:01,292 --> 00:48:04,774
<i>But it's Lauda who takes the ﬂag
here at Kyalami.</i>

694
00:48:04,852 --> 00:48:06,502
<i>James Hunt comes home second</i>

695
00:48:06,572 --> 00:48:09,018
<i>to confirm his championship
challenge at last</i>

696
00:48:09,092 --> 00:48:10,821
<i>and score his first points</i>

697
00:48:10,852 --> 00:48:12,422
<i>of the season.</i>

698
00:48:13,012 --> 00:48:16,858
That wind you can feel
is me breathing down your neck.

699
00:48:16,972 --> 00:48:18,974
Next time I'll have you.

700
00:48:19,932 --> 00:48:21,343
We'll see in Spain.

701
00:48:41,852 --> 00:48:45,652
<i>James Hunt finally takes
his first victory of the season</i>

702
00:48:45,692 --> 00:48:48,218
<i>here in Spain, after a brilliant drive.</i>

703
00:48:48,332 --> 00:48:50,539
It was only a matter of time.

704
00:48:57,732 --> 00:49:00,702
Luca, don't you think it's time
to tell them?

705
00:49:07,412 --> 00:49:09,733
- It's too wide.
- Disqualified.

706
00:49:10,132 --> 00:49:12,499
- What?
- You're disqualified.

707
00:49:12,572 --> 00:49:14,256
How can we be disqualified?

708
00:49:14,372 --> 00:49:16,181
- 1.5 centimetres.
- It's the same car.

709
00:49:16,252 --> 00:49:18,414
<i>Giustissimo.</i>

710
00:49:22,572 --> 00:49:23,733
You fucking...

711
00:49:23,852 --> 00:49:26,696
<i>...McLaren M23
has proved very controversial here.</i>

712
00:49:28,732 --> 00:49:30,575
Just make it narrower. I don't care how.

713
00:49:30,692 --> 00:49:32,740
New rear suspension.
New wishbones.

714
00:49:32,772 --> 00:49:35,582
I wanna make sure
this thing is legal, no doubts.

715
00:49:35,692 --> 00:49:38,093
Well, then we'd better move the
oil coolers back to the old position.

716
00:49:38,172 --> 00:49:40,379
With the oil coolers back, the
wing brackets need to be changed, too.

717
00:49:40,412 --> 00:49:41,538
Fuck.

718
00:49:41,612 --> 00:49:43,740
What the fuck
d'you think we're doing?

719
00:49:53,412 --> 00:49:55,892
<i>And with Hunt disqualified
from his Spain win,</i>

